hemselves at a huge disadvantage. The government that bailed out corporations considered too economically important to fail also negotiates settlements permitting giant firms to avoid the consequences of criminal convictions. Presenting detailed data from more than a decade of federal cases, Brandon Garrett reveals a pattern of negotiation and settlement in which prosecutors demand admissions of wrongdoing, impose penalties, and require structural reforms. However, those reforms are usually vaguely defined. Many companies pay no criminal fine, and even the biggest blockbuster payments are often greatly reduced. While companies must cooperate in the investigations, high-level employees tend to get off scot-free. The practical reality is that when prosecutors face Hydra-headed corporate defendants prepared to spend hundreds of millions on lawyers, such agreements may be the only way to get any result at all. Too Big to Jail describes concrete ways to improve corporate law enforcement by insisting on more stringent prosecution agreements, ongoing judicial review, and greater transparency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCorporate governancexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aCorporate governance; Law and legislation; United States. 0aCorporation lawzUnited StatesxCriminal provisions. 0aCorporation law; United States; Criminal provisions. 0aCorporationsxCorrupt practiceszUnited States. 0aCorporations; Corrupt practices; United States. 0aCriminal liability of juristic personszUnited States. 0aCriminal liability of juristic persons; United States. 0aProsecutionzUnited States. 0aProsecution; United States. 0aTort liability of corporationszUnited States. 0aTort liability of corporations; United States. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHa